esley Powell, William Temple Hornaday, and Olaus and Adolph Murie—homegrown midwestern field biologists who either headed east to populate major research centers or went west to conduct their fieldwork along the frontier. From the pioneering work of Victor Shelford, Henry Chandler Cowles, and Aldo Leopold to contemporary insights from biologists such as Jim Furnish and historians such as William Cronon, Lannoo’s unearthing of American—and particularly midwestern—field biologists reveals how these scientists influenced American ecology, conservation biology, and restoration ecology, and in turn drove global conservation efforts through environmental legislation and land set-asides. This Land Is Your Land reveals the little-known legacy of midwestern field biologists, whose ethos and discoveries have enabled us to preserve and understand not just their land, but all lands.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBiologistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aBiologistszUnited States. 0aBiologists-United States-Biography. 0aBiologyxFieldworkzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aBiology-Fieldwork-United States-History. 0aConservation biologyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aConservation biology-United States-History. 0aNature studyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aNature study-United States-History. 7aNATURE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106885800 cprintz978022635847540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226358505423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226358505/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles